{"title": "39 fall ill in gas leak at Malaysia airport facility", "tags": "asia", "timestamp": "2024-07-04", "content": "KUALA LUMPUR - A gas leak on July 4 at an engineering section of Kuala Lumpur\u2019s international airport saw 39 people fall ill, a Malaysian emergency services official said.\n\u201cA total of 39 victims suffered from dizziness and nausea,\u201d local rescue officer Muhammad Nur Khairi Samsumin said in a statement.\nHe added that 24 victims were discharged, 14 others were at the Air Disaster Unit receiving care and one was hospitalised.\nAll of those affected work for three companies operating at the facility.\nThe incident did not disrupt air travel at the country\u2019s top airport.\nMr Muhammad Nur said the leaked gas was identified as methyl mercaptan, and the source was an \u201cunused tank\u201d at the facility.\n\u201cWork to cover the leak was being done by the emergency crew,\u201d he said, adding that the tank would be dismantled and disposed off.\nMr Muhammad Nur said methyl mercaptan is added to liquefied petroleum gas to give it a smell, alerting people to any leaks. The gas has a strong odour akin to rotten cabbages. AFP"}